One of the most significant impacts of Nietzsche's ideas on contemporary thought is his critique of traditional moral values and religious beliefs. Nietzsche argued that morality and religion were based on fear and weakness, and that true strength and happiness could only be achieved through a radical reevaluation of traditional values. This idea has been a source of inspiration for many philosophers, artists, and activists who have sought to challenge traditional social norms and create a more just and equitable world.

Another significant impact of Nietzsche's ideas is his emphasis on the individual as the center of existence. Nietzsche argued that individuals should strive to become self-actualized, independent, and creative, rather than being bound by the constraints of tradition or society. This has inspired many people to pursue their own paths in life, to embrace their individuality, and to challenge the status quo.

In addition to his philosophical influence, Nietzsche's works have also had a significant impact on popular culture. His ideas have been adapted into numerous films, novels, and other forms of art, and he has become a cultural icon for rebels, outcasts, and those who reject traditional norms.

Overall, Nietzsche's ideas have had a profound impact on contemporary thought and culture, inspiring individuals to challenge traditional values and pursue their own paths in life. His legacy continues to be felt today in the work of philosophers, artists, activists, and others who seek to create a more just and equitable world.
source: "Hvaða hugmyndir í heimspeki Nietzsches hafa enn áhrif á nútíma menningu?"

Few-shot learning (FSL) er ein af lykilframtíðarstigum í tölvulærdómi og vekur mikla athygli. Í þessari grein er fókusinn á FSL vandamálinu við skilning á samræðum, sem inniheldur tvo náið tengda verkefni: ásetningu á tilgangi og fyllingu á reitum. Það hefur verið sannað að samræðuskilningur hagnist mikið á að læra samhliða báðum undirverkefnunum. Hins vegar er slík samhliða lærdómur erfiður í few-shot aðstæðum: á annarri hendi aukast erfiðleikar við að módelera tenginguna milli verkefnanna vegna þess að sýnatalsþrek magnar erfiðleikana; á hinni hendi er enn frekar lítið rannsakað hvernig á að læra samhliða mörgum verkefnum í few-shot umhverfinu. Í svari við þetta kynnum við FewJoint, fyrsta FSL mælikvarða fyrir samhliða samræðuskilning. FewJoint býður upp á nýtt safn með 59 mismunandi samræðusviðum úr raunverulegum iðnaðarforritagreinum og kóðaplattform til að auðvelda uppsetningu FSL tilrauna, sem er vonast til að muni stuðla að rannsóknum á þessu sviði. Þar að auki finnum við að ófullkominn framkomur í few-shot umhverfinu leiðir oft til hávaða deilingar milli undirverkefnanna og truflar samhliða lærdóm. Til að takast á við þetta, leiðbeinum við reitum með skýrum tilgangsupplýsingum og leggjum fram nýja trúargæsluhátt sem hindrar lágt-traust tilgangsupplýsingar til að tryggja gæði deilingarinnar. Að auki kynnum við Reptile-háttar meta-lærdómsaðferð til að ná betri almennun í óséðum few-shot sviðum. In this chapter, we focus on few-shot learning task, which is the problem of predicting a class label from few training samples. While few-shot learning has been shown to be effective in many domains, it faces several challenges that prevent it from generalizing to other domains. In particular, the current few-shot learning models struggle with generalization to unseen domains due to insufficient training data and lack of appropriate representation learning. To address this issue, we propose FewJoint, a new few-shot learning framework for human-object interactions. FewJoint introduces a new dataset containing 59 diverse object interaction scenes from real-world scenarios and an open-source code platform for conducting experiments on few-shot human-object interaction tasks. We evaluate FewJoint against several state-of-the-art few-shot learning models and show that our model outperforms previous models in terms of generalization to unseen domains. Moreover, our analysis reveals that lack of appropriate representation learning is one of the main reasons for the poor generalization in few-shot human-object interaction tasks. To address this issue, we introduce new representation learning strategies by leveraging human pose information and propose new data augmentation strategies that allow the model to learn more reliable representations from limited training data. Finally, we demonstrate that Reptile meta-learning approach can be used to further improve the performance of few-shot human-object interaction tasks. Through extensive experiments on two downstream tasks and three different benchmarks, we show that our approach achieves new state of the art performance on few-shot human object interaction tasks.
